    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradual Rollout Strategies with Feature Flags"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shipping 100% of traffic to a new code path on day one is the riskiest possible deployment. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradual rollout",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " uses feature flags to expose new behaviour to an increasing fraction of users, pausing at each threshold to confirm that error rates and latency remain stable. This limits the blast radius of any regression to the fraction of users currently in the experiment."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A 1% canary that detects a regression protects 99% of users. A rollback from a flag update takes seconds; a rollback from a full deploy takes minutes and leaves an incident record."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This sub-subtopic covers three rollout strategies \u2014 percentage, user segment, and ring \u2014 their implementation patterns, and the automated signals that advance or halt a rollout."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three gradual rollout strategies: percentage rollout, user segment targeting, and ring deployment, with automated rollback trigger conditions",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 1: Percentage Rollout"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest strategy routes a deterministic percentage of users to the new code path. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deterministic",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " means a given user always sees the same experience for the same flag state \u2014 achieved by hashing the user ID rather than drawing a random number on each request:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# src/rollout.py\nimport hashlib\n\ndef is_in_canary(user_id: str, flag_name: str, pct: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Returns True for the same user_id/flag_name combination every call.\n\n    Uses SHA-256 of (flag_name + user_id) so different flags produce\n    independent splits from the same user population.\n    \"\"\"\n    if pct <= 0:\n        return False\n    if pct >= 100:\n        return True\n    key = f\"{flag_name}:{user_id}\"\n    digest = hashlib.sha256(key.encode()).hexdigest()\n    # Take the first 8 hex chars (32 bits) and scale to 0-99\n    bucket = int(digest[:8], 16) % 100\n    return bucket < pct\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# src/flags.py (extended with percentage support)\nimport yaml, os\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom src.rollout import is_in_canary\n\ndef is_enabled(flag_name: str, user_id: str | None = None) -> bool:\n    cfg = _REGISTRY.get(flag_name)\n    if cfg is None:\n        raise KeyError(f\"Flag '{flag_name}' is not registered\")\n\n    state = cfg[\"state\"]\n    if state in (\"retired\", \"registered\"):\n        return False\n    if state == \"full_on\":\n        return True\n\n    # Check env var override (ops rollback)\n    env_val = os.getenv(cfg[\"rollback_env_var\"])\n    if env_val is not None:\n        return env_val.lower() == \"true\"\n\n    if state == \"default_off\":\n        return False\n\n    if state == \"canary\":\n        pct = cfg.get(\"canary_pct\", 0)\n        if user_id is None:\n            return False  # no user context \u2192 exclude from canary\n        return is_in_canary(user_id, flag_name, pct)\n\n    return False\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At each threshold \u2014 1%, 10%, 50% \u2014 wait for a minimum of one hour (or until 1000 affected requests) before advancing. The canary percentage lives in `flags.yml` and is updated via PR, creating a traceable advance history."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 2: User Segment Targeting"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Percentage rollout is blind to user characteristics. Segment targeting routes by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "attributes",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 internal employees first, then beta opt-ins, then general availability. This gives the engineering team and willing early adopters first exposure before any external user sees the change:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# src/segments.py\nfrom enum import IntEnum\n\nclass Segment(IntEnum):\n    INTERNAL  = 0   # @company.com email\n    BETA      = 1   # opted into beta program\n    STANDARD  = 2   # all other authenticated users\n    ANONYMOUS = 3   # unauthenticated\n\ndef user_segment(user: dict) -> Segment:\n    email = user.get(\"email\", \"\")\n    if email.endswith(\"@company.com\"):\n        return Segment.INTERNAL\n    if user.get(\"beta_opt_in\"):\n        return Segment.BETA\n    if user.get(\"user_id\"):\n        return Segment.STANDARD\n    return Segment.ANONYMOUS\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# config/flags.yml \u2014 segment-targeted flag\nflags:\n  token_dashboard:\n    description: \"Per-user token usage in admin dashboard\"\n    owner: \"@eve\"\n    team: product\n    state: canary\n    canary_segments: [internal, beta]   # only these segments see it\n    created: 2025-07-10\n    expires_after: 2025-09-15\n    rollback_env_var: FEATURE_TOKEN_DASHBOARD\n    tracking_issue: \"#1215\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# src/flags.py \u2014 segment-aware is_enabled\nfrom src.segments import user_segment, Segment\n\nSEGMENT_ORDER = [Segment.INTERNAL, Segment.BETA, Segment.STANDARD, Segment.ANONYMOUS]\nSEGMENT_NAMES = {s.name.lower(): s for s in Segment}\n\ndef is_enabled(flag_name: str, user: dict | None = None) -> bool:\n    cfg = _REGISTRY.get(flag_name)\n    if cfg is None:\n        raise KeyError(f\"Flag '{flag_name}' is not registered\")\n\n    state = cfg.get(\"state\")\n    if state == \"full_on\":\n        return True\n    if state in (\"retired\", \"registered\", \"default_off\"):\n        return False\n\n    # Segment-based canary\n    if \"canary_segments\" in cfg:\n        if user is None:\n            return False\n        seg = user_segment(user)\n        allowed = {SEGMENT_NAMES[s] for s in cfg[\"canary_segments\"]}\n        return seg in allowed\n\n    # Percentage-based canary\n    if \"canary_pct\" in cfg:\n        user_id = user.get(\"user_id\") if user else None\n        return is_in_canary(user_id or \"\", flag_name, cfg[\"canary_pct\"])\n\n    return False\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Strategy 3: Ring Deployment"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ring deployment is a named variant of segment targeting used by teams with an established testing tier hierarchy. "
